The hawkish policy camp, nicknamed the "dragon slayers," demands a bigger U.S. military presence in Asia to restrict China's sea access and act as a barrier to any bullying of weaker nations.At the other end of the spectrum on China_policy_@DOC are the analysts Logan_@P1 calls_@REL "panda huggers," who are betting that a focus on trade and diplomacy over military might will force China to democratize and become a more trusted U.S. partner.The administration's current plans call for deploying 2,000 Marines to Australia and four coastal combat shipsto Singapore - hardly terrifying prospects for the Chinese, the hawks complain.But critics of the notion that the pivot lacks military chops point out that there's already a huge U.S. military presence in the Asia Pacific, larger than during the most recent Republican administrations.
