Bookmark the permalink .Last updated: December 10, 2014 at 11:30 amdocno: 439167New energy innovation report highlights central role of emerging economies07:00, Technology/Energy & Green Tech--------------------------------------------------------------------------------Full size image"High-Energy_Innovation_@DOC" is_a_new_report_from_@REL the Consortium_for_Science,_Policy_and_Outcomes_@ORG and The Breakthrough Institute.Innovation in clean_energy_technologies_@TECH is a truly global phenomenon, and the most active efforts to develop next-generation technologies are in rapidly industrializing countries, where energy demand is high and deployment opportunities are abundant.From advanced_nuclear_reactor_technologies_@TECH in China and solar_@TECH projects in Brazil to South African experiments in clean_coal_@TECH and Indian_shale_gas_exploration_@TECH, the global landscape for clean_energy_innovation_@TECH has never been more fertile.To take advantage of these opportunities, governments must strengthen international collaborative efforts to supply the global public of clean, cheap energy, says a new report from a group of 12 energy_scholars_@P3.
High-Energy_Innovation_@DOC is the second of three reports in the Climate_Pragmatism_project_@DOC, a partnership of Arizona_State_University's_Consortium_for_Science,_Policy,_and_Outcomes_@ORG and The Breakthrough Institute.High-Energy_Innovation_@DOC evaluates_@REL four clean_energy_technologies_@TECH - shale gas, carbon_capture_and_storage_@TECH, nuclear, and solar_@TECH - and finds that, in all cases, industrializing countries are making significant investments and leveraging international collaborations in order to make energy cleaner, cheaper and more reliable.Nearly all of the growth in energy markets and the majority of new_energy_technologies_@TECH deployed in the next several decades are projected to occur in the developing world.
